{
  "title": "Candidate Generation Techniques for PYMK: A Deep Dive into Graph, Similarity, and Heuristics-Based Approaches",
  "summary": "This article explores the candidate generation (CG) techniques used in the PYMK recommendation system at LinkedIn. The system employs three main approaches: graph-based CG (N-hop neighbors and PPR), similarity-based CG (embedding-based retrieval), and heuristics-based CG (simple rules and filters). These techniques are combined into a final candidate pool, which is then passed to rankers to generate personalized recommendations. The article also discusses offline evaluation metrics, future considerations, and the impact of these techniques on user engagement and retention.",
  "key_points": [
    {
      "section": "Graph-Based Candidate Generation",
      "details": [
        "N-hop neighbors: Candidates are generated by traversing the graph up to 2-3 hops away from the viewer.",
        "Personalized PageRank (PPR): A graph-based technique that propagates information recursively across the network, allowing for the inclusion of candidates who are 5-6 hops away from the viewer.",
        "Graph Neural Networks (GNNs): Despite advancements in GNN embeddings, they have not yet proven effective in generating N-hop neighbors or PPR candidates due to issues like graph isomorphism."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section": "Similarity-Based Candidate Generation",
      "details": [
        "Embedding-Based Retrieval (EBR): Member embeddings are learned using a Two Tower Neural Network, which pulls impressed candidates closer to the viewer's embedding.",
        "Negative Sampling: Used to make the computation of the denominator in the softmax function feasible, with techniques like in-batch negatives, random negatives, and nearest neighbor negatives.",
        "Impressions as Positive Instances: Using impressed candidates as positives helps avoid bias against infrequent members and improves recall."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section": "Heuristics-Based Candidate Generation",
      "details": [
        "Simple rules and filters are used to generate candidates, such as members who recently interacted with the viewer, members who clicked on notifications, or members who searched the viewer's profile."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section": "Final Candidate Pool",
      "details": [
        "Candidates from all three CG techniques are aggregated into a final pool, with each candidate having a score (common connections, PPR score, or dot-product similarity).",
        "A 1-hot encoded categorical feature indicating the CG technique is used in rankers to capture the global popularity of each technique."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section": "Offline Evaluation",
      "details": [
        "Recall@k is the primary evaluation metric for the CG stage.",
        "Entropy over a categorical attribute is used as a secondary metric to evaluate candidate diversity.",
        "The distribution of CG sources in the candidate pool is analyzed to identify skewness."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section": "Future Considerations",
      "details": [
        "Exploring the use of GNN embeddings to approximate graph-based CG.",
        "Making parts of the CG system near-realtime to improve freshness of candidates.",
        "Investigating deep sequential learning for candidate generation."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section": "Impact and Conclusion",
      "details": [
        "A/B tests showed increased member engagement and retention.",
        "CG techniques improved both frequent and infrequent member engagement.",
        "The article concludes that candidate generation is a critical component of large-scale recommendation systems."
      ]
    }
  ],
  "conclusion": "The PYMK system demonstrates a robust and diverse approach to candidate generation, combining graph-based, similarity-based, and heuristics-based techniques to ensure a high-quality and personalized recommendation experience. The system's continuous exploration of new methods, such as GNN embeddings and near-realtime processing, highlights its commitment to innovation and improvement in recommendation systems."
}

