{
  "title": "Enhancing RAG Accuracy with Agentic Frameworks and LLM-as-Judge at Uber",
  "summary": "This article discusses the implementation of an enhanced agentic RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) framework at Uber to improve the accuracy and relevance of chatbot responses in the engineering security and privacy domain. The framework includes improvements in document processing, the use of LLM-powered agents for query optimization and source identification, and the integration of the LLM-as-Judge framework for automated evaluation. These enhancements have led to significant improvements in the performance of the on-call copilot Genie.",
  "key_points": [
    {
      "section": "Introduction",
      "content": "The article introduces the need for improving the accuracy of chatbot responses in domain-specific contexts such as engineering security and privacy. It highlights the limitations of traditional RAG systems and the benefits of adopting an agentic RAG framework."
    },
    {
      "section": "Document Processing Enhancements",
      "content": "The article discusses the transition from PDFs to Google Docs for more accurate text extraction. It also covers the use of LLM-powered enrichment processes to improve formatting and metadata for better semantic search and retrieval."
    },
    {
      "section": "Agentic RAG Answer Generation",
      "content": "The article explains the use of LLM-powered agents in the pre-retrieval and post-processing steps to improve context relevance and enhance extracted content before answer generation. It also describes the integration of a BM25-based retriever alongside traditional vector search."
    },
    {
      "section": "Challenges and Solutions",
      "content": "The article outlines the challenges faced in improving accuracy, including high SME involvement and slow evaluation, and marginal gains in accuracy. It discusses the use of automated evaluation with generative AI and the agentic RAG framework to overcome these challenges."
    },
    {
      "section": "LLM-as-Judge for Automation of Batch Evaluation",
      "content": "The article describes the use of the LLM-as-Judge framework to automate the evaluation of chatbot responses. It explains how this framework helps in identifying improvement areas and enhancing performance by providing structured scores and feedback."
    },
    {
      "section": "Implementation with LangChain and LangGraph",
      "content": "The article discusses the development of the agentic RAG framework using Langfx and LangGraph, highlighting the scalability and developer-friendly nature of these tools."
    },
    {
      "section": "Use Cases at Uber",
      "content": "The article concludes with the successful implementation of the EAg-RAG framework for the on-call copilot Genie within the engineering security and privacy domain. It highlights the significant improvements in the accuracy and relevancy of the golden test-set answers."
    }
  ],
  "conclusion": "The implementation of the enhanced agentic RAG framework at Uber has led to significant improvements in the accuracy and relevance of chatbot responses in the engineering security and privacy domain. The use of LLM-powered agents, improved document processing, and the integration of the LLM-as-Judge framework have enabled faster iterations and more effective directional experimentation, ensuring that the on-call copilot Genie can reliably support security and privacy teams without risking inaccurate guidance."
}

